 542 -class CDF(collections.MutableMapping): 

 543      """Python object representing a CDF file. 
 544   
 545      Opening existing 
 546      ================ 
 547      Open a CDF by creating a CDF object, e.g.: 
 548      C{cdffile = pycdf.CDF('cdf_filename.cdf')} 
 549      Be sure to L{close} or L{save} when done. 
 550   
 551      CDF supports the U{with 
 552      <http://docs.python.org/tutorial/inputoutput.html#methods-of-file-objects>} 
 553      keyword, like other file objects, so:: 
 554          with pycdf.CDF('cdf_filename.cdf') as cdffile: 
 555              do brilliant things with the CDF 
 556      will open the CDF, execute the indented statements, and close the CDF when 
 557      finished or when an error occurs. The U{python docs 
 558      <http://docs.python.org/reference/compound_stmts.html#with>} include more 
 559      detail on this 'context manager' ability. 
 560   
 561      CDF objects behave like a python 
 562      U{dictionary 
 563      <http://docs.python.org/tutorial/datastructures.html#dictionaries>}, 
 564      where the keys are names of variables in the CDF, and the values, 
 565      L{Var} objects. As a dictionary, they are also U{iterable 
 566      <http://docs.python.org/tutorial/classes.html#iterators>} and it is easy 
 567      to loop over all of the variables in a file. Some examples: 
 568        1. List the names of all variables in the open CDF cdffile::

 571           epoch = cdffile['Epoch']

 578           print len(cdffile)

 582                  data = cdffile.copy()

 584      Normally it's better to treat the CDF as a dictionary and access only 
 585      the data needed, which will be pulled transparently from disc. See 
 586      L{Var} for more subtle examples.

1086 -class Var(collections.MutableSequence): 

1087      """A CDF variable. 
1088   
1089      Reading 
1090      ======= 
1091      This object does not directly store the data from the CDF; rather, 
1092      it provides access to the data in a format that looks like a Python 
1093      list. General list information is available in the python docs: 
1094      U{1<http://docs.python.org/tutorial/introduction.html#lists>}, 
1095      U{2<http://docs.python.org/tutorial/datastructures.html#more-on-lists>}, 
1096      U{3<http://docs.python.org/library/stdtypes.html#typesseq>}. 
1097   
1098      A record-varying variable's data are viewed as a hypercube of dimensions 
1099      n_dims+1 and are indexed in row-major fashion, i.e. the last 
1100      index changes most frequently / is contiguous in memory. If 
1101      the CDF is column-major, the data are transformed to row-major 
1102      before return. The extra dimension is the record number. 
1103   
1104      Non record-varying variables are similar, but do not have the extra 
1105      dimension of record number. 
1106   
1107      Variables can be subscripted by a multidimensional index to return the 
1108      data. Indices are in row-major order with the first dimension 
1109      representing the record number. If the CDF is column major, 
1110      the data are reordered to row major. Each dimension is specified 
1111      by standard Python 
1112      U{slice<http://docs.python.org/tutorial/introduction.html#strings>} 
1113      notation, with dimensions separated by commas. The ellipsis fills in 
1114      any missing dimensions with full slices. The returned data are 
1115      lists; Python represents multidimensional arrays as nested lists. 
1116      The innermost set of lists represents contiguous data. 
1117   
1118      Degenerate dimensions are 'collapsed', i.e. no list of only one 
1119      element will be returned if a single subscript is specified 
1120      instead of a range. (To avoid this, specify a slice like 1:2, 
1121      which starts with 1 and ends before 2). 
1122   
1123      Two special cases: 
1124        1. requesting a single-dimension slice for a 
1125           record-varying variable will return all data for that 
1126           record number (or those record numbers) for that variable. 
1127        2. Requests for multi-dimensional variables may skip the record-number 
1128           dimension and simply specify the slice on the array itself. In that 
1129           case, the slice of the array will be returned for all records. 
1130      In the event of ambiguity (i.e. single-dimension slice on a one-dimensional 
1131      variable), case 1 takes priority. 
1132      Otherwise, mismatch between the number of dimensions specified in 
1133      the slice and the number of dimensions in the variable will cause 
1134      an IndexError to be thrown. 
1135   
1136      This all sounds very complicated but it's essentially attempting 
1137      to do the 'right thing' for a range of slices. 
1138   
1139      As a list type, variables are also U{iterable 
1140      <http://docs.python.org/tutorial/classes.html#iterators>}; iterating 
1141      over a variable returns a single complete record at a time. 
1142   
1143      This is all clearer with examples. Consider a variable B_GSM, with 
1144      three elements per record (x, y, z components) and fifty records in 
1145      the CDF. Then: 
1146        1. C{B_GSM[0, 1]} is the y component of the first record. 
1147        2. C{B_GSM[10, :]} is a three-element list, containing x, y, and z 
1148           components of the 11th record. As a shortcut, if only one dimension 
1149           is specified, it is assumed to be the record number, so this 
1150           could also be written C{B_GSM[10]}. 
1151        3. C{B_GSM[...]} reads all data for B_GSM and returns it as a 
1152           fifty-element list, each element itself being a three-element 
1153           list of x, y, z components. 
1154   
1155      Multidimensional example: consider fluxes stored as a function of 
1156      pitch angle and energy. Such a variable may be called Flux and 
1157      stored as a two-dimensional array, with the first dimension

1160      Assume 100 records stored in the CDF (i.e. 100 different times). 
1161        1. C{Flux[4]} is a list of ten elements, one per energy step, 
1162           each element being a list of 18 fluxes, one per pitch bin. 
1163           All are taken from the fifth record in the CDF. 
1164        2. C{Flux[4, :, 0:4]} is the same record, all energies, but 
1165           only the first four pitch bins (roughly, field-aligned). 
1166        3. C{Flux[..., 0:4]} is a 100-element list (one per record),

1169      This slicing notation is very flexible and allows reading

1201      Writing 
1202      ======= 
1203      As with reading, every attempt has been made to match the behavior of 
1204      Python lists. You can write one record, many records, or even certain 
1205      elements of all records. There is one restriction: only the record 
1206      dimension (i.e. dimension 0) can be resized by write, as all records 
1207      in a variable must have the same dimensions. Similarly, only whole 
1208      records can be deleted. 
1209   
1210      For these examples, assume Flux has 100 records and dimensions [2, 3]. 
1211        1. C{Flux[0] = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]} rewrites the first record 
1212           without changing the rest. 
1213        2. C{Flux[...] = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]} writes a new first record 
1214           and deletes all the rest. 
1215        3. C{Flux[99:] = [[[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]],  [[11, 12, 13], [14, 15, 16]]]} 
1216           writes a new record in the last position and adds a new record after. 
1217        4. C{Flux[5:6] = [[[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]],  [[11, 12, 13], [14, 15, 16]]]} 
1218           inserts two new records between the current number 5 and 6. This 
1219           operation can be quite slow, as it requires reading and rewriting the 
1220           entire variable. (CDF does not directly support record insertion.) 
1221        5. C{Flux[0:2, 0, 0] = [1, 2]} changes the first element of the first 
1222           two records but leaves other elements alone. 
1223        6. C{del Flux[0]} removes the first record. 
1224        7. C{del Flux[5]} removes record 5 (the sixth). Due to the need to work 
1225           around a bug in the CDF library, this operation can be quite slow. 
1226        8. C{del Flux[...]} deletes I{all data} from C{Flux}, but leaves the 
1227           variable definition intact.
